        "title": "hashing and checking password in java",
        "body": "<p>Hi I write a simple database program where I need to have users. I write a simple program to test my idea and it seems to work, but I wonder if my idea is correct.<\/p>\n\n<p>I hash passwords with salt:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Random random = new Random();\nbyte[] salt = new byte[16];\nrandom.nextBytes(salt);\nKeySpec spec = new PBEKeySpec(\"pass123\".toCharArray(), salt, 65536, 128);\nSecretKeyFactory f = SecretKeyFactory.getInstance(\"PBKDF2WithHmacSHA512\");\nbyte[] hash = f.generateSecret(spec).getEncoded();\nBase64.Encoder enc = Base64.getEncoder();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>store them as a string hash + salt in database:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String index  = enc.encodeToString(salt) + \"$\"+ enc.encodeToString(hash);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and when user is logging get my string from database and check if pass is correct:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>String stored[] = index.split(\"\\\\$\");\nKeySpec spec1 = new PBEKeySpec(\"haslo1234fdfgds\".toCharArray(), stored[0].getBytes(), 65536, 128);\nSecretKeyFactory f1 = SecretKeyFactory.getInstance(\"PBKDF2WithHmacSHA512\");\nbyte[] hash1 = f.generateSecret(spec1).getEncoded();\nif(stored[1].equals(enc.encodeToString(hash1))) return true;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I know that in Base64 is decoder, but I wonder if I have to use it when this solution seems to work?\nI am new in this so there is a huge possibility I forget about something, that's why I want to ask if my idea is ok.<\/p>\n",
